WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:16.298
Art stories - Slavín

2
00:00:16.488 --> 00:00:22.236
Shortly after the Second World War arose the idea to build a monument in Bratislava

3
00:00:22.236 --> 00:00:25.236
for the fallen soldiers of the Red Army.

4
00:00:25.762 --> 00:00:30.520
One which could compete with the Castle by their very dominance

5
00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:35.060
and would be visible from the main roads into the city.

6
00:00:35.940 --> 00:00:38.761
Back in the 19th century, maybe even earlier,

7
00:00:38.761 --> 00:00:43.921
(Alexandra Kusá – Director of the Slovak National Gallery)  
during the Slovak National Revival and the Slovak Brotherhood,

8
00:00:43.921 --> 00:00:46.986
when they tried to devise rituals and mythologies,

9
00:00:46.986 --> 00:00:53.007
they came up with the idea of Slavín as a place where all Slavic heroes would go after death.

10
00:00:53.007 --> 00:00:57.809
Slavín is very specific name for something which pertains to Slavs

11
00:00:57.809 --> 00:01:02.800
and has a mythological character and which naturally involves funeral rites.

12
00:01:05.234 --> 00:01:09.225
The preparation for what Slavín should look like was carried out in several stages.

13
00:01:09.225 --> 00:01:12.524
Naturally, it was necessary to act immediately after the war,

14
00:01:12.524 --> 00:01:17.772
because it is not only a memorial but also a cemetery and it has various functions.

15
00:01:17.772 --> 00:01:23.288
What is very interesting is to see how the process became more and more political.

16
00:01:23.288 --> 00:01:31.717
The memorial was increasingly becoming some sort of affirmation of the Soviet influence on Czechoslovakia,

17
00:01:31.717 --> 00:01:39.566
which became reality only in 1948, but precisely this memorial extended the influence back to 1945.

18
00:01:41.190 --> 00:01:49.024
In 1953 was issued the invitation to tender, in which participated several leading architects of the time.

19
00:01:49.831 --> 00:01:55.376
Part of their proposals was inclusion of sculptures of many other famous artists:

20
00:01:55.376 --> 00:01:57.253
Tibor Bártfay,

21
00:01:57.253 --> 00:01:58.838
Ján Kulich,

22
00:01:58.838 --> 00:02:00.530
Jozef Kostka,

23
00:02:00.540 --> 00:02:02.245
Ladislav Snopek,

24
00:02:02.245 --> 00:02:04.050
Alexander Trizuljak

25
00:02:04.050 --> 00:02:05.530
and others...

26
00:02:09.043 --> 00:02:16.692
The art of Socialist realism was announced as the aim of our national cultural policy in 1948,

27
00:02:16.692 --> 00:02:18.961
but the change in architecture unsurprisingly takes some time.

28
00:02:18.961 --> 00:02:26.624
This is why the tender kept getting prolonged as everyone kept anxiously waiting for what exactly will Social realism be.

29
00:02:26.725 --> 00:02:30.779
This was the spirit of the proposed projects of the architects,

30
00:02:30.779 --> 00:02:34.985
who were more used to working in the modernist style.

31
00:02:34.985 --> 00:02:42.007
The tender was won by Ján Svetlík and his vertical conception of sleek pylon

32
00:02:42.007 --> 00:02:47.647
topped with a statue of a soldier raising a flag.

33
00:02:47.647 --> 00:02:51.968
The author of this central statue is Alexander Trizuljak.

34
00:02:54.949 --> 00:03:02.258
The concept is based on the statue of Archangel Michael on Castel Sant'Angelo in Rome.

35
00:03:02.258 --> 00:03:07.026
It depicts a soldier flying a flag, which is the symbol of victory,

36
00:03:07.026 --> 00:03:10.026
who is stepping on the swastika.

37
00:03:10.026 --> 00:03:14.252
The statue expands into space in its perspective.

38
00:03:14.252 --> 00:03:24.289
If we saw the statue on the eye level, it would seem disproportionately wide in shoulders and head area.

39
00:03:24.741 --> 00:03:30.903
(Klement Trizuljak – Alexander Trizuljak's Son) 
This widening in perspective foreshortening

40
00:03:30.903 --> 00:03:33.763
ensured proportional perception.

41
00:03:33.763 --> 00:03:40.051
The statue itself was enormous in size,

42
00:03:40.051 --> 00:03:44.011
eleven-meter tall figure plus the flag,

43
00:03:44.011 --> 00:03:48.334
which required cooperation with a structural designer.

44
00:03:48.334 --> 00:03:56.507
It was necessary to build an internal structure which could carry the weight of the clay piled onto the model.

45
00:03:56.987 --> 00:04:04.449
When my father saw the pipes and profiles and the way they were welded together,

46
00:04:04.449 --> 00:04:10.043
he gained inspiration for his next work,

47
00:04:10.043 --> 00:04:14.543
as if he jumped straight into Modernism.

48
00:04:21.978 --> 00:04:25.525
(Eva Trizuljaková –Alexander Trizuljak's Wife) 
He did a welding course and then he began welding himself.

49
00:04:25.525 --> 00:04:30.513
This was the period in the 1960s and 1970s,

50
00:04:30.513 --> 00:04:34.513
when everyone was scandalized by what that Trizuljak made.

51
00:04:34.513 --> 00:04:40.810
Modernists didn’t accept him among them because he used to be part of the Socialist realism movement.

52
00:04:47.228 --> 00:04:52.272
My father was never a member of the Communist Party,

53
00:04:52.272 --> 00:04:58.139
he worked his way up to his position purely by his efforts.

54
00:04:58.139 --> 00:05:04.510
His area and his space was this professional engagement.

55
00:05:05.577 --> 00:05:15.770
After this period of artistic boom and prominent social standing came the Occupation in 1968,

56
00:05:15.776 --> 00:05:21.789
in April further lessons from the crisis development and thus began the period of Normalization.

57
00:05:21.789 --> 00:05:27.545
They used so-called religious argument against my father;

58
00:05:27.545 --> 00:05:33.129
as a person who 'hasn't come to terms with the religious issues',

59
00:05:33.129 --> 00:05:36.539
he cannot teach at the Academy of Fine Arts and Design.

60
00:05:39.477 --> 00:05:43.679
Those times very horribly deformed by the political situation.

61
00:05:44.522 --> 00:05:54.640
Everyone took care to be friendly with the right people because your career was entirely dependant on politics.

62
00:05:56.663 --> 00:06:00.972
Many people took him for a communist flunky,

63
00:06:00.972 --> 00:06:07.298
even though he never was, and the Communists themselves never respected him.

64
00:06:07.499 --> 00:06:11.672
One of the legends is that it represents the letter D for Deus.

65
00:06:11.672 --> 00:06:15.956
When you look at the silhouette, there is a particular outline.

66
00:06:15.956 --> 00:06:20.208
Another outline is B for Boh – God.

67
00:06:21.415 --> 00:06:26.305
When we asked father, because other people were also asking question, he always denied it.

68
00:06:26.485 --> 00:06:31.758
People from the Christian community were accusing him

69
00:06:31.758 --> 00:06:36.518
that the tower on the Calvary Church in Bratislava was pulled down because of Slavín.

70
00:06:36.518 --> 00:06:47.263
This is untrue - the cause was definitely the pressure from the Party organs and bypassing of the approval of the then Bishop Ambróz Lazík.“

71
00:06:47.263 --> 00:06:53.787
His deputy, who was installed in that position by the Party, gave his approval in the absence of the Bishop.

72
00:06:53.787 --> 00:07:01.311
The tower on the Church was pulled down on the basis of this deception.

73
00:07:01.311 --> 00:07:10.999
Another story, also untrue, says that my father declared in 1968 that if he knew that Russian occupation forces would come,

74
00:07:10.999 --> 00:07:14.785
he would have never built the monument.

75
00:07:14.785 --> 00:07:19.270
However, my father used to say that those are two separate issues.

76
00:07:19.270 --> 00:07:22.505
The sacrifice of those people nevertheless remains.

77
00:07:22.505 --> 00:07:25.425
Those people deserve this honour.

78
00:07:25.755 --> 00:07:30.000
The monument was finished on 4th April 1960

79
00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:37.292
on the occasion of the 15th anniversary of the Liberation of Bratislava in such form as we know it today.

80
00:07:37.955 --> 00:07:41.845
Besides being popular spot for romantic meetings,

81
00:07:41.845 --> 00:07:47.513
Slavín is an important architectural piece of work of the post-war Slovakia,

82
00:07:47.513 --> 00:07:52.524
uniting the art of Modernism with the art of Socialist realism.

